	<header>
		<h1 class="exhibition-title">ABOUT</h1>
		<p>
			‘And the word was God (神)’ examines the relationship between
			Chinese and English languages in Australia. A collaboration between
			three first-generation Chinese Australians working in video art,
			poetry and typography design, each artist draws upon their lived
			experience to explore how the languages they speak are used,
			exchanged and transformed across time. Through the sympathy between
			three modalities of practice, this exhibition discovers dynamic
			connections between the past, present and future of language
			exchange in Australia.
		</p>

		<p>
			And the word was God (神) is an immersive exploration of language
			and its appearances in a world where diverse cultures have the
			opportunity to thrive side by side with each other. It invites
			audiences to reflect upon their own experiences with language in
			order to foster dialogue and understanding on the path to a future
			of multicultural flourishing.
		</p>

		<p class="CJK">
			and the word was God (神) 考察了澳大利亞漢語和英語之間的關繫。
			這是三位從事視頻藝術、詩歌和版式設計的第一代澳大利亞華人之間的合作，每位藝術家都利用自己的生活經驗來探索他們所説的語言如何隨着時間的推移而使用、交流和轉變。
			通過三種實踐方式之間的共鳴，本次展覽髮現了澳大利亞語言交流的過去、現在和未來之間的動態聯繫。
		</p>

		<p>
			and the word was God (神)
			是對語言及其在多元文化有機會共同繁榮的世界中的表現的身臨其境的探索。
			它邀請觀衆反思自己的語言經曆，以促進對話和理解，邁向多元文化繁榮的未來。
		</p>
	</header>
	<br />
	<h2 class="h2-title">Artists 艺术家</h2>
	<br />
	<h3 class="h3-title">Ming Liew 刘明</h3>
	<p>
		Ming Liew is a lens-based artist and a PhD student at the Royal
		Melbourne Institute of Technology. His practice draws upon his
		Chinese-Australian bicultural identity, combining ethnography and visual
		storytelling to examine the immigrant experience in contemporary
		Australia. Accentuating the paradoxes between lived and prescribed
		sociocultural realities, Ming uses his artworks to advocate for
		understanding that transcends linguistic, cultural, and social barriers.
	</p>

	<p class="CJK">
		Ming Liew 是一位基于镜头的艺术家，也是皇家墨尔本理工学院的博士生。
		他的实践利用了他的中澳双文化身份，结合民族志和视觉叙事来审视当代澳大利亚的移民经历。
		明用他的艺术作品强调了生活与规定的社会文化现实之间的悖论，倡导超越语言、文化和社会障碍的理解。
	</p>
	<br />
	<h3 class="h3-title">Ben Yi-Yu Qin 秦奕宇</h3>
	<p>
		Ben Qin is a poet and the Projects Coordinator at the Museum of Chinese
		Australian History. Observing a principle of the fundamental entwinement
		between form and content in writing, he composes poetry specifically to
		interact with unconventional media. His poetry demonstrates how media
		are not without their own saturation of meaning and how the use of new
		forms of media, from domestic furniture to photographs, deepen our
		manners of understanding. Through these unexpected appearances for
		poetry, Ben explores an emerging Chinese Australian experience.
	</p>

	<p class="CJK">
		秦奕宇本是一位诗人，也是澳大利亚华人历史博物馆的项目协调员。
		他遵循写作中形式与内容基本交织的原则，专门为与非传统媒体互动而创作诗歌。
		他的诗歌展示了媒体并非没有自身饱和的意义，以及从家用家具到照片等新媒体形式的使用如何加深我们的理解方式。
		通过这些意想不到的诗歌出现，本探索了澳大利亚华人的新兴经历。
	</p>

	<br />
	<h3 class="h3-title">Xinyuan (Caesar) Li 李鑫源</h3>
	<p>
		Xinyuan (Caesar) Li is an independent designer and a Studio Assistant at
		RMIT University in the School of Design and Social Context. His design
		practice involves using digital technologies to augment Western design
		styles with traditional Chinese aesthetics, in typography, type design
		and identity design. He speculates on the co-existence of visual forms
		in the English and Chinese languages to cultivate transcultural
		narratives in the realm of contemporary design.
	</p>
	<p class="CJK">
		李新元 (Caesar) Li
		是一位独立设计师，也是工作室助理皇家墨尔本理工大学设计与社会背景学院。
		他的设计实践涉及使用数字技术来增强西方设计具有中国传统审美的风格，在版式、字体设计上和身份设计。
		他推测视觉形式的共存英语和汉语培养跨文化当代设计领域的叙事。
	</p>

